{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620664"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:45:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:45:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16644"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16644"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.38,0.03,0.13,0.46]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9335"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76224"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9335"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16644"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61728"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5248"},{"type":"tags","id":"10106"},{"type":"tags","id":"10135"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22108"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22377"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76224"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAnti-androgens are medications commonly used in the treatment of prostate cancer and other androgen-dependent conditions. These drugs work by interfering with androgen signalling pathways.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of anti-androgens?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stimulates oestrogen receptor activity","Blocks conversion of testosterone to dihydrotestosterone","Increases testosterone metabolism in the liver","Decreases testosterone production in the testes","Competitively binds to androgen receptors"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAnti-androgens primarily work through \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompetitive binding to androgen receptors\u003C/strong\u003E. By occupying these receptors, they prevent testosterone and dihydrotestosterone from binding and initiating their biological effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates oestrogen receptor activity\u003C/strong\u003E - anti-androgens are specific for androgen receptors and do not directly affect oestrogen signalling\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks conversion of testosterone to dihydrotestosterone\u003C/strong\u003E - this is the mechanism of 5-alpha reductase inhibitors like finasteride, not anti-androgens\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases testosterone metabolism in the liver\u003C/strong\u003E - anti-androgens do not significantly affect testosterone metabolism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases testosterone production in the testes\u003C/strong\u003E - this is the mechanism of gonadotrophin-releasing hormone analogues, not anti-androgens\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy blocking androgen receptors, these medications prevent androgens from stimulating the growth and survival of prostate cancer cells, making them effective in hormone-sensitive prostate cancer treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anti-androgens work by competitively binding to androgen receptors, preventing testosterone and dihydrotestosterone from exerting their effects.","Anti-androgens are used in the treatment of prostate cancer to block the growth-promoting effects of androgens on cancer cells.","Common anti-androgens include bicalutamide and enzalutamide."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61728"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16644"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61728"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T14:31:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T14:32:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9335"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76224"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Leve